<subSubSection id="C363F4C9FF81FF9BF1CDFD35EF9AFDD1" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="392" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC6A742FF81FF9AF1CDFD35EA0BFD21" blockId="4.[166,1224,671,730]" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">
C o m m e n t. Three species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C79DCC1FF81FF9AF3A4FD0AED12FD42" box="[690,802,672,697]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90D7B50FF81FF9AF3A4FD0AED12FD42" box="[690,802,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">Diaeretus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known worldwide, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C79DCC1FF81FF9AF574FD0AEEDDFD22" baseAuthorityName="Haliday" baseAuthorityYear="1834" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucopterus">
<emphasis id="B90D7B50FF81FF9AF574FD0AEEDDFD22" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">D. leucopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only one species present in the Palearctic 
<collectingRegion id="49BD69A0FF81FF9AF236FD15ED43FD22" box="[800,883,703,729]" country="Iraq" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">Region</collectingRegion>
(Yu et al., 2012).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC6A742FF81FF9AF1CDFD45EA80FC52" blockId="4.[166,1225,751,938]" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">
С o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s. 
<taxonomicName id="4C79DCC1FF81FF9AF30FFD5AEC8DFCF2" baseAuthorityName="Haliday" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[537,701,751,777]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucopterus">
<emphasis id="B90D7B50FF81FF9AF30FFD5AEC8DFCF2" box="[537,701,751,777]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">D. leucopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="1342BBC7FF81FF9AF3D8FD45ED3CFCF1" box="[718,780,751,778]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[275,1082,1029,1703]" captionTargetId="figure-329@4.[256,1104,1015,1723]" captionText="Fig. 4. Diaeretus leucopterus, ♀ (1–5) and Diaeretiella rapae, ♀ (6–10): 1, 6 — antenna; 2, 7 — forewing; 3, 8 — propodeum; 4, 9 — petiole; 5, 10 — ovipositor sheath (5 — after Takada, 1968). Рис. 4. Diaeretus leucopterus, ♀ (1–5) и Diaeretiella rapae, ♀ (6–10): 1, 6 — усик; 2, 7 — переднее крыло; 3, 8 — проподеум; 4, 9 — стебелёк; 5, 10 — створки яйцеклада (5 — по: Takada, 1968)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6467460" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6467460/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">fig. 4</figureCitation>
) morphologically is similar to species from monotypic genus 
<emphasis id="B90D7B50FF81FF9AF0A7FCA5EC65FCD2" box="[433,597,783,809]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicName id="4C79DCC1FF81FF9AF0A7FCA5EC05FCD2" authorityName="Stary" authorityYear="1960" box="[433,565,783,809]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Diaeretiella</taxonomicName>
—
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C79DCC1FF81FF9AF34CFCBAED1EFCD2" authority="M'Intosh" authorityName="M'Intosh" box="[602,814,783,809]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapae">
<emphasis id="B90D7B50FF81FF9AF34CFCBAEC8BFCD2" box="[602,699,784,809]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">D. rapae</emphasis>
M’Intosh
</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs by:1) antenna with 16–18segments; 2) mesoscutum without notauli; 3) shorter radial vein of forewing: its length equal to stigma width; 4) propodeum with transverse carina and without central areola; 5) petiole with slightly visible longitudinal tubercle and without central carina; 6) almost square ovipositor sheath, not thinned to the apex; 7) form of the apex of ovipositor sheath.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF06F7CAFF81FF9AF1B0F910EDCBF8CB" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6467460" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6467460" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6467460/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" startId="4.[166,199,1722,1744]" targetBox="[275,1082,1029,1703]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph id="8BC6A742FF81FF9AF1B0F910ED9CF910" blockId="4.[166,1224,1719,1771]" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">
Fig. 4. 
<emphasis id="B90D7B50FF81FF9AF1F0F911EF88F934" box="[230,440,1722,1744]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicName id="4C79DCC1FF81FF9AF1F0F911EF84F934" baseAuthorityName="Haliday" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[230,436,1722,1744]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucopterus">Diaeretus leucopterus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<specimenCount id="9D7F6CCBFF81FF9AF0ABF91DEFFEF92B" box="[445,462,1719,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
(
<emphasis id="B90D7B50FF81FF9AF0CAF910EFCFF934" box="[476,511,1722,1743]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">1–5</emphasis>
) and 
<emphasis id="B90D7B50FF81FF9AF321F910ECD6F92B" box="[567,742,1722,1744]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicName id="4C79DCC1FF81FF9AF321F910ECD3F92B" box="[567,739,1722,1744]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapae">Diaeretiella rapae</taxonomicName>
